This is the first of a 4 lab sequence working with more realistic data. In this lab, you will explore LHC particle physics data (Files/Dataset/LHC). You will explore features of the data and optimize the discovery signficance by applying event selections.

Dataset

There are two groups of datasets in different pT ranges. For each pT range, there is simulated data and pseudo-experiment data. The easiest way to read the pseudo-experiment data is through pandas.read_hdf() in python, but you can also read it directly with hdf5 ('block0_items' contains the feature names, 'block0_values' contains the data values).

  • low transverse momentun (PT) 250~500 GeV/c: Sample_pt_250_500

Reading Data

The pickle module implements binary protocols for serializing and de-serializing a Python object structure. The data format used by pickle is Python-specific. This has the advantage that there are no restrictions imposed by external standards such as JSON or XDR (which cant represent pointer sharing); however it means that non-Python programs may not be able to reconstruct pickled Python objects.

Study Pickle manual https://wiki.python.org/moin/UsingPickle

In this section, a brief introduction about the detector coorindate, jet physics and jet substructure are given. Extended readings are provided for you to dive into further details.

Detector and coordinate

The ATLAS detector, one of the two general purpose detectors at the LHC, is used as the example to demonstrate the general concept of collider detectors. A typical event display of a di-jet physics process is recorded by the ATLAS detector as shown below.

The beam pipe is centered on the cylindrical axis of symmetry of the detector. The proton beams are moving along the z-axis. Particles produced in the collisions emerge from the center of the detector in all directions. ATLAS has been designed to record the paths and energies of the particles emerging from the collisions.

Pseudorapidity $\eta$ is a geometric quantity. It is a function of polar angle $\theta$ that goes from $\inf$ to $\inf$ as $\theta$ goes from 0 to $\pi$. Azimuthal angle $\phi$ goes around the beam.

The extended reading can be found in https://arxiv.org/pdf/1709.04533.pdf

What is a Jet?

A jet is a collection of particles that go towards the same direction in the detector. Intuitively, they come from bremsstrahlung (showering) and fragmentation of a primordial hard quark or gluon. In practice, jets must be defined from experimental observables, namely the 4-momenta of the observed particles in the event. There is no unique jet definition. One desirable propertyof a jet definition is that it allows for a calculation done at the parton level (quarks and gluons) to agree with a measurement done at the particle level (pions and protons). Another desirable feature is that a jet algorithm should be local in the detector not pulling in particles fromfar away. This property is important from an experimental point of view to reduce systematic uncertainty of jet measurements. The simplest way to define a jet is to draw a cone of size $=\sqrt{\Delta \eta^2+\Delta \phi^2}$ around some particle and include everything in that cone as the jet.

Why do we study Jet Substructure?

The importance of physics at transverse momenta pt much greater than the resonance particle mass has implications for the structure of the final state because at high transverse momenta, signature particles, Ws, Zs, Higgs bosons and top quarks, have very collimated decays (due to their relativistic boost). Standard approaches for identifying these particles (i.e. recombining different jets) fail because all the decay products end up in a single jet. The physics discovery relies on capability of identifying hadronic decays of boosted heavy Higgs particles with two-pronged decays from QCD quarks or gluons which generate a significant fraction of jets with large masses (or equivalently with 2 or 3-pronged substructure). The substructure variables computed from 4-momenta of constituents of jets can play essential roles for this classification task.

A short introduction of jet clustering algorithms and jet substructure varibles can be found in https://arxiv.org/abs/1201.0008.

def histograms(var):
    plt.hist(qcd[var],bins=60,histtype='step',label='QCD')

Task3 Significance optimization (4 points)

Now we want to scan over d2 to find a good cut on d2 to increase our significance. The siginificance formula is given below(it's a good exercise to think about the derivation of the formula), and it is in the unit of $\sigma$:

$Significance = \frac{N_{signal}}{\sqrt{N_{bkg}}}$

We want to reject as many bkg as possible while keep the signal to make signal more visible(siginificant).

Now, think the following questions:

  1. Inspect the d2 distribution after you apply the mass cut, how does it change compared to that without any mass cut?
  2. Let's say you choose a d2 cut value of 4, do you want to keep the histogram below 4 of above 4? Which makes signal more siginificant?
  3. What range can be chosen to scan the d2 cut?

After you have some ideas, choose a range to scan d2. For each d2 value you can calculate a significane. Then plot significance vs. d2 cut value, choose the cut value corresponding to 3 $\sigma$. Now plot the Mass distributions with the mass cut and with the d2 cut. What do you observe in this plot? What is the significance value with these two cuts(mass and t2)?

A good checking is that compare the significance before any d2 cut and with a very large d2 cut.

The plot below is a exmaple of how the signifiance vs cut value might look like:

In[]:
d2range = np.linspace(0.01,12,600)
signif=[]
# Calculate weights for each value within range
# Added tiny value to ensure qcdweight != 0
for i in d2range:
    qcdweight=len(qcd.loc[(qcd['d2'] <= i)])/(10**(5)*20000) + 1e-99
    higgsweight=len(higgs.loc[(higgs['d2'] <= i)])/(10**(5)*100)
    signif.append(higgsweight/np.sqrt(qcdweight))

plt.scatter(d2range,signif)
plt.plot(d2range,signif)
plt.xlabel('d2 cut range')
plt.ylabel('Significance')
plt.title('Significance vs d2 cut range')
Out[]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Significance vs d2 cut range')
In[]:
# Applying cuts for where significance > 2.5
sig_loc = np.where(np.array(signif) > 2.5)[0]
d2_min, d2_max = d2range[sig_loc[0]], d2range[sig_loc[-1]]

# Masks
higgsd2mask=np.logical_and.reduce((higgs['mass'] >= 120, higgs['mass'] <= 130,
                                   higgs['d2']<d2_max,higgs['d2']>d2_min))
qcdd2mask=np.logical_and.reduce((qcd['mass'] >= 120, qcd['mass'] <= 130,
                                   qcd['d2']<d2_max,qcd['d2']>d2_min))
filt_higgs_mass=higgs['mass'][higgsd2mask]
filt_higgs_d2=higgs['d2'][higgsd2mask]
filt_qcd_mass=higgs['mass'][qcdd2mask]
filt_qcd_d2=higgs['d2'][qcdd2mask]

# Yields & weights
higgs_yield=len(filt_higgs_mass)
qcd_yield=len(filt_qcd_mass)

higgs_weight=100/higgs_yield
qcd_weight=20000/qcd_yield

# Mass cut plots
plt.hist([filt_qcd_mass,filt_higgs_mass],bins=60,histtype='step',
         stacked=True,fill=False,density=False,label=['QCD','Higgs'],
         weights=[np.full(qcd_yield,qcd_weight),np.full(higgs_yield,higgs_weight)])
plt.xlabel('Mass (GeV)')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Weighted)')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Signal & Background Mass (Mass & d2 cut)')
plt.show()

# d2 cut plots
plt.hist([filt_qcd_d2,filt_higgs_d2],bins=60,histtype='step',
         stacked=True,fill=False,density=False,label=['QCD','Higgs'],
         weights=[np.full(qcd_yield,qcd_weight),np.full(higgs_yield,higgs_weight)])
plt.xlabel('d2')
plt.ylabel('Frequency (Weighted)')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Signal & Background d2 (Mass & d2 cut)')

  1. This was already discussed above
  2. The histogram should be below 4. Mainly because there isn't much above 4, but also because that's the max range you're looking at. This then makes the signal more significant because the majority of the peak is below 4.
  3. I personally chose 0.01 to 12

The mass distribution with both cuts has a much higher frequency & the Higgs peak is much closer to the QCD peak. Or perhaps it's just hard to tell because the values are larger.
